  <static seed="1580" source="Contrib/PCC/BasicAlgebra/RationalEquations/solveRationalEquations4.pg">
    <statement><p>Solve the equation.</p>
<p><m>\displaystyle{ {\frac{t-4}{t-5}} = {\frac{t}{t-3}} }</m></p>
<p><fillin characters="34" name="AnSwEr0001"/></p>
</statement>
    <answer>
      <p>
        <m>\left\{6\right\}</m>
      </p>
    </answer>
    <solution><p>To get rid of all fractions in this equation, we multiple all terms with the common denominator. In this equation, the common denominator is <m>{\left(t-5\right)\mathopen{}\left(t-3\right)}</m>.</p>
<p><m>\displaystyle{\begin{aligned}
   {\frac{t-4}{t-5}} \amp = {\frac{t}{t-3}} \\
   {\frac{t-4}{t-5}} \cdot {\left(t-5\right)\mathopen{}\left(t-3\right)} \amp = {\frac{t}{t-3}} \cdot {\left(t-5\right)\mathopen{}\left(t-3\right)} \\
   {\left(t-4\right)\mathopen{}\left(t-3\right)} \amp = {t\mathopen{}\left(t-5\right)} \\
   {t^{2}-3t-4t+12} \amp = {t^{2}-5t} \\
   -2t \amp = -12 \\
   t \amp = 6
\end{aligned}
    }</m></p>
<p>We must check solutions when we solve rational equations. By the original equation, the domain condition is <m>{\left(t-5\right)\mathopen{}\left(t-3\right)} \ne 0</m>, which is equivalent to <m>t \ne 5</m> and <m>t \ne 3</m>. This doesn<rsq/>t conflict with the solution above, so the solution is <m>t = 6</m>.</p>
</solution>
